Example 3 – Tracking accelerating aircraft

  • In this example, we track an aircraft moving with constant acceleration with the α − β filter.

Consider an aircraft moving radially toward (or away from) a radar in a onedimensional
world. The α − β filter parameters are:
• α = 0.2.
• β = 0.1.
The track-to-track interval is 5 seconds.

You can see a constant gap between true or measured values and estimates. The gap
is called a lag error. Other common names for the lag error are:

• Dynamic error
• Systematic error
• Bias error
• Truncation error

Example 4 – Tracking accelerating aircraft using the α−β −γ filter

  • Let’s take the scenario from the previous example: an aircraft that moves with
    a constant velocity of 50m/s for 20 seconds and then accelerates with a constant
    acceleration of 8m/s2 for another 35 seconds.

  • The α - β -γ filter parameters are:

  • α = 0.5.

  • β = 0.4.

  • γ = 0.1.

  • The track-to-track interval is 5 seconds.
